The purpose of this project was to better understand proof presentation and proof comprehension at the undergraduate level. In upper-level university mathematics classes, lectures largely consist of professors presenting proofs of theorems to their students, yet students have serious difficulties understanding these proofs. In this project, I investigated the causes of students' difficulties and designed instruction to help students overcome these difficulties.

Key contributions from this study included:

(1) A description of how and why mathematicians read the published proofs of their colleagues in their professional practice;

(2) A taxonomy of unproductive beliefs that most mathematics majors hold that inhibit the understanding of the proofs that they read;

(3) A list of strategies that undergraduates can use to better understand the proofs that they read;

(4) A theoretical model for what it means to understand a proof and a description of how proof comprehension tests can be generated;

(5) A description of mathematicians' beliefs and practices in how and why they present proofs in their classes, including what they hope students gain from these proofs and what they do to increase the chances that their learning goals are attained;

(6) The design of instruction to help students learn the strategies that we believe will foster proof comprehension.

Work from this grant has yielded 14 journal publications in prestigious outlets including Journal for Research in Mathematics Education, Cognition and Instruction, Educational Psychologist, and Educational Studies in Mathematics, two invited worshops at conferences by the Mathematical Association of America (MAA) to help mathematicians improve their teaching, and numerous conference presentations.

